			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Let me give you guys some prospective</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes, that is one perspective.  One of many.
<br />

<br />
Again, how much DPS do you have when OOM?  SV+Gloves is more efficient.  Casala's point is also huge and severly overlooked.  No magic based Evocation DD at all.
<br />

<br />

<br />
This list is assuming 65th mage, access to ornate/elemental gloves, most spells.  Which totally within reach for any 65th mage.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Not limited by aggro or mana: </span>Evocation Wins
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Limited by aggro:</span>  Max DPS less valuable, no benefit to Max DPS.  Conj. Wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Limited by Mana:</span> Most Efficient = best.  Conj. Wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Limited by aggro and mana:</span>  No benefit to DPS, Efficientcy rules, Conj. Wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">PBAoE nuking:</span> Evocation Wins
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Fire Resisted:</span> Conj. Wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Magic Resisted:</span> Could go either way.  Depends on other restrictions.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Pet-Cleric tactic:</span> Conjuration heavy, Conj. Wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Rod Dispenser/Summoner:</span> Conj. Wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Chain Casting Pets W/O reclaim:</span> Conj. Wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Chain Casting Pets with reclaim: </span>No clear winner, too small to matter.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">You Aggro Kiting, huge HP mob:</span>  Need to recast pets as you will lose aggro.  Efficientcy matters a ton.  Conj. wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">You Aggro Kiting, small HP mob:</span> If you can hold aggro with Conjuration nukes, no need for higher DPS.  If you lose aggro with Conjuration nukes then Evocation will hold it a bit longer.  When even Evocation loses aggro, Conjuration will win because now you are recasting pets.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Aggro Kite fast EXP group:</span>  As long as the pulls are decently fast, efficientcy is everything.  Conj. Wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Aggro Kite slow EXP group:</span>If you get time to med back to full  between kills, mana does not matter.  Just DPS.  Evocation wins unless fire is resisted (like PoF tables), then Conjurations wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Debuffing mobs in a raid:</span>  No winner, does not matter.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Soloing a tough mob, DPS needed:</span> Evocation Wins as long as pet lives, Fire not resisted, and you don't run OOM.  Any of those happen, and Conjuration will probably win.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Soloing a tough mob, Efficientcy needed:</span> Conjuration all the way, since it's just flat out more efficient.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">CoTH mage:</span> Conjuration wins.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Charming Mage:</span> Charm&Malosinia both Alteration, Mez Conjuration, VERY DPS limited since charm aggro passed to mage.  Conjuration Wins.
<br />

<br />
Disagree if you like, this is pretty much how I see it.  A few small places where Evocation wins.  If you do those situations nearly all the time, then perhaps it's better for you.  I'm pretty much even across the board in terms of what I do.  There is no majority of which playstyle I use, and Conjuration is the clear winner in the majority of them.<br />_________________<br /><Center><b>Eandori
<br />
<span style="font-style: italic"><a href="http://forum.magecompendium.com/viewtopic.php?t=13760" target="_blank" class="postlink">"The pinnacle of pet offensive power can be achieved at level 50 with the epic pet. Does this make sense?"</a></span>
<br />
</center></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
